iMany people keep their inventory of photos and videos for their		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itravels, parties, or whatever important moments of their lives. If you		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iare into taking photos and recording videos and like keeping all of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithem, you will likely fill up hard drives after hard drives. If you		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idon't want to keep adding more drives to your collection, you may also		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itry to compress your photos and videos.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSpeaking of compression, a common method is to reduce the resolution		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iof images. I've used the good old Microsoft Office Picture Manager (that		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icomes with Office 2003) and its built-in one-key image compression.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBehind the scenes, it's actually downsampling images to JPEG files of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iaround 1024x768. One major drawback is that a lot of the details are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icompletely lost. Even if you think you can accept the losses by the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itime you archive the files, with the development of technology, those		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilosses may become significant one day. For example, in mid-2000, a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icommon monitor had a resolution of 1024x768, which is why Microsoft		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOffice Picture Manager chose to compress images to this resolution.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut when they are enlarged on a modern 1080p or even 4K monitor, the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iloss of details makes images blurry, and such losses are irreversible.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore, I wish that the quality is almost not affected at all while		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icompressing photos and videos. Help from modern video and image		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icompression algorithms is needed to achieve this. Early compression		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ialgorithms come with limitations from their eras since they are unable		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito perform complicated compression or decompression operations with		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe CPU performance and RAM size limits and produce badly compressed		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifiles (larger in file size). Modern algorithms, on the other hand, are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idesigned with multicore processors and large RAMs in mind and can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icompress the files to a smaller size. For example, the most popular		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iJPEG image format is invented back in 1992, and its compression rate		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iis being laughed at by WebP, invented in 2010. According to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hthis study by Google	URL:https://developers.google.com/speed/webp/docs/webp_study	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i, WebP is 25% smaller than JPEG for a set of sample files used.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAnother example is LZMA used by 7-Zip, which fully utilizes multicore		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprocessors and eats a few gigs of RAM, and in turn, produces results		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imuch smaller than Zip files' Deflate algorithm.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
