i## Image Archival - HEIF		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHere are the reasons I chose HEIF:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- HEIF specification was finalized in 2015.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- HEIF is currently widely used on iOS devices as the default format		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  for cameras. Android 9 also added support as well. In the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  foreseeable future, software support for HEIF will become mature		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  quickly.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- The major advantage is that it uses H265 to encode photos, which		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  fully utilizes the maturity of video encoders. In addition, hardware		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  acceleration can be used if necessary.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHEIF files can be generated by ImageMagick. But on Arch Linux, the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iImageMagick from Arch repo doesn't come with HEIF support by default,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand we need to install `libheif` additionally. We can also install `exiftool` ,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhich copies EXIF information (including camera model, aperture,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ishutter, ISO parameters, locations, etc) to HEIF files.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  pikaur -S imagemagick libheif perl-image-exiftool		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe next three commands convert all JPG files to HEIC (file extension		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifor HEIF), transfer EXIF information, and remove the JPG files:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  for x in **/*.jpg; do magick "$x" "${x%.jpg}.heic"; done		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  for x in **/*.jpg; do exiftool -overwrite_original -tagsFromFile "$x" -all:all "${x%.jpg}.heic"; done		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  rm -rf **/*.jpg		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe HEIC files produced should be around half the size of JPEG files.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThere aren't many parameters to tune for HEIF, and the default		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isettings are enough for almost everyone. By contrast, in my testing,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iif I adjust quality with parameters, the generated image will be huge (even		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilarger than JPEG) but with no noticeable differences in image quality.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
